Dr. Fullfölja: (Chuckles) As far as the detection of a sound source goes, no technology is even remotely close or will be in the distant future to what you and I have already brought to the table; ears.
附加记录：    

Actually, human ears pretty much suck when it comes to localizing sound. Dog ears are much better, but if you really want to get the job done quickly and cheaply, use an array of microphones and some off-the-shelf software to compare the inputs.

Since sound waves travel through air at a fixed rate of 343m / s, you can use the timing between when one microphone detects a spike and when another microphone detects a spike to figure out which one is further away from the source of the sound. Use four microphones, and you can use triangulation techniques such as multilateration to determine the direction in 2D that the sound is coming from. Presumably, a larger array of microphones could extend this to 3D, but it might involve writing custom code.





